    <script>
      (function () {
        const sidebar = document.getElementById('demo-toggleable-sidebar');
        const trigger = document.getElementById('demo-toggleable-sidebar-trigger');
        trigger.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const willCollapse = !sidebar.classList.contains('is-collapsed');
          if (willCollapse) {
            // Close any open submenus first so they animate shut alongside
            // the width slide instead of snapping to display:none mid-collapse.
            sidebar.querySelectorAll('.collapse.show').forEach((el) => {
              Stisla.bs.Collapse.getOrCreateInstance(el).hide();
            });
          }
          sidebar.classList.toggle('is-collapsed');
          sidebar.style.width = willCollapse ? '4.25rem' : '18rem';
          trigger.setAttribute('aria-expanded', willCollapse ? 'false' : 'true');
        });
      })();
    </script>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>That is the whole script. From here you can persist the state to <code>localStorage</code>, swap the icon, animate the icon flip, move the trigger to a topbar button, reopen submenus when expanding, and so on. The script also closes any open submenus before collapsing the sidebar. It uses Bootstrap 5's <code>Collapse</code> API (<code>Stisla.bs.Collapse</code> when you load Stisla's bundle, <code>bootstrap.Collapse</code> if you import Bootstrap separately) so the submenu height animation runs alongside the width slide. Without that step, the <code>display: none</code> on collapsed submenus would snap them shut instead of animating.</p>
  </section>

